This paper deals with the typing and evaluation of lambda-terms in different logics, specifically Elementary and Light Affine Logic (EAL, LAL). The focus is on the complexity and completeness of optimal reduction using Lamping's algorithm. These topics are closely related to the areas of logic, programming languages, and computational complexity, which are covered by several arXiv CS sub-categories. 

cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is the most likely sub-category, as the paper deals with the typing and evaluation of lambda-terms in different logics. 

cs.PL (Programming Languages) is also a likely sub-category, as the paper discusses the evaluation of lambda-terms using Lamping's algorithm, which is a technique used in programming language implementation. 

cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is another possible sub-category, as the paper deals with the complexity of optimal reduction using Lamping's algorithm, which is a computational problem. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a less likely sub-category, but still possible, as the paper discusses the use of a simple geometry of interaction model for proving soundness and completeness. 

cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is another possible sub-category, as the paper deals with the complexity of optimal reduction using Lamping's algorithm and proves that it has a polynomial bound.
